# Pork

For other uses, see [Pork (disambiguation)](/Pork_(disambiguation)).

*   "Pig meat" redirects here. For other uses, see [Pig Meat](/Pig_Meat_(disambiguation)).

![Pork belly cut, showing layers of muscle and fat](/File:Pork_belly_cut.jpg)
[Pork belly](/Pork_belly) cut, showing layers of muscle and fat
![A pig being slow-roasted on a rotisserie](/File:Roast_pig_on_spit.jpg)
A pig being slow-roasted on a [rotisserie](/Rotisserie)

[Pork](/Pork) is the rather uninspired, yet perfectly descriptive, [culinary name](/Culinary_name) for the [meat](/Meat) derived from the [domestic pig](/Pig) (*Sus domesticus*). Despite its somewhat contentious status in certain cultures, it persistently holds its position as the second most commonly consumed type of meat globally, trailing only behind poultry. This claim, though often cited, has been subject to a [dubious](/Wikipedia:Accuracy_dispute) designation in some circles, which one might [discuss](/Talk:Pork) if one had the time or inclination. However, humanity's relationship with the pig is undeniably ancient, with archaeological evidence of systematic pig [husbandry](/Animal_husbandry) stretching back an impressive 8,000 to 9,000 [BCE](/BCE). It seems even in antiquity, the appeal of a well-fed pig was universally understood.

Beyond its immediate consumption, [pork](/Pork) is also extensively enjoyed in various preserved forms; [curing](/Curing_(food_preservation)) being the timeless method that significantly extends the otherwise fleeting [shelf life](/Shelf_life) of these porcine products. This foresight, born of necessity, has given rise to a pantheon of culinary staples: [ham](/Ham), [gammon](/Gammon_(meat)), [bacon](/Bacon), and the ubiquitous [pork sausage](/Sausage) stand as prime examples of preserved pork's enduring legacy. The intricate art of [charcuterie](/Charcuterie), a specialized branch of [cooking](/Cooking), is almost entirely devoted to the creation of these meticulously prepared [meat](/Meat) products, many of which owe their existence, flavor, and texture to the humble pig.

Geographically, [pork](/Pork)'s popularity is far from uniform but undeniably widespread. It remains a cornerstone of the diet in much of the [Western world](/Western_world), particularly dominant in the culinary traditions of [Central Europe](/Central_Europe). Its influence extends vigorously across [East](/East_Asia) and [Southeast Asia](/Southeast_Asia), encompassing regions such as [Mainland Southeast Asia](/Mainland_Southeast_Asia), the [Philippines](/Philippines), [Singapore](/Singapore), and [East Timor](/East_Timor). Here, in many [Asian cuisines](/Asian_cuisine), especially within [China](/China) (including the bustling metropolis of [Hong Kong](/Hong_Kong)) and the vibrant culinary landscape of [Northeast India](/Northeast_India), the meat is not merely appreciated but highly prized, often for its distinctive fat content and a texture that lends itself beautifully to a myriad of preparations.

Yet, for all its global appeal, [pork](/Pork) remains a forbidden food for significant populations. Certain religions and cultures maintain strict dietary laws that [prohibit pork consumption](/Religious_restrictions_on_the_consumption_of_pork), most notably the adherents of [Islam](/Islamic_dietary_laws) and [Judaism](/Kashrut). Such prohibitions, deeply embedded in theological and cultural frameworks, create a stark contrast in global consumption patterns, proving that even something as seemingly universal as food can be a profound marker of identity and belief.

## History

*   See also: [Charcuterie](/Charcuterie) and [Animal husbandry § History](/Animal_husbandry)

This section, like much of human history, often "needs expansion." One might wonder if the past is ever truly settled, or if we're simply condemned to perpetually add to it. Rest assured, the fundamental facts are here, awaiting your (or my) more detailed consideration.

The story of the pig's integration into human society begins millennia ago. Evidence suggests that these intelligent and adaptable creatures were first domesticated in the fertile crescent of [Mesopotamia](/Mesopotamia) around 13,000 BCE. Not long after, or perhaps even concurrently, the pig emerged as one of the earliest animals to be brought under human control in [ancient China](/Ancient_China). Archaeological findings at [Cishan](/Cishan_culture), for instance, point to pig domestication occurring around 8,000 BP, which translates to approximately 6,000 BC. It seems humanity recognized the pig's potential early on, a testament to its efficiency as a food source.

![Pig being prepared in France during the mid-19th century.](/File:Pig_preparation_France_19thC.jpg)
Pig being prepared in [France](/France) during the mid-19th century.

The culinary realm of [charcuterie](/Charcuterie) represents a sophisticated evolution of the desire to preserve and enhance [meat](/Meat). This specific branch of [cooking](/Cooking) is meticulously dedicated to a wide array of prepared meat products, predominantly, though not exclusively, derived from the pig. Think of the rich, smoky flavors of [bacon](/Bacon), the salty succulence of [ham](/Ham), the diverse profiles of [sausage](/Sausage), the elegant layers of [terrines](/Terrine_(food)), the artful presentation of [galantines](/Galantine), the smooth textures of [pâtés](/P%C3%A2t%C3%A9s), and the luxurious richness of [confit](/Confit). While these preparations were originally conceived as ingenious methods to preserve meats long before the advent of modern refrigeration, their continued popularity today is less about necessity and more about the distinctive and complex flavors that these intricate preservation processes impart.

In 15th-century [France](/France), the meticulous regulation of tradesmen in the food production industry was overseen by local [guilds](/Guild) in each city. Among these, the guild of the *charcutiers* held a special place. Members of this esteemed guild were responsible for producing a traditional and extensive range of cooked, salted, and dried meats. The specific offerings often varied, sometimes quite distinctively, from one region to another, reflecting local tastes and available ingredients. Curiously, the only "raw" meat the *charcutiers* were permitted to sell was [unrendered](/Rendering_(food_processing)) [lard](/Lard), a testament to the strictures of the time. Beyond this, the *charcutier* was a master of many porcine arts, expertly preparing numerous items including various [pâtés](/P%C3%A2t%C3%A9s), the rich and spreadable [rillettes](/Rillettes), a multitude of [sausages](/Sausage), the ever-popular [bacon](/Bacon), savory [trotters](/Pig%27s_trotters), and the distinctive [head cheese](/Head_cheese). The complexity and variety of these preparations underscore the deep historical roots of pork in European culinary tradition.

Before the relentless march of mass production and the subsequent re-engineering of pigs in the 20th century, pork in both Europe and North America was traditionally considered an autumn delicacy. Pigs and other livestock were typically brought to slaughter in the autumn, having spent the spring growing and the summer fattening. This seasonal availability of the meat in Western culinary history led to a natural and enduring pairing: [apples](/Apple), which were (and still are) harvested in late summer and autumn, became a staple accompaniment to fresh pork. While the modern era has blessed us with the year-round availability of both meat and fruits, the popularity of this classic combination on Western plates has, remarkably, not diminished. Some traditions, it seems, are too good to discard, even when their original rationale has faded into history.

## Consumption patterns

Pigs, in their various forms, remain the second most widely consumed animal worldwide. This isn't just a casual observation; it's a statistical reality, with pork accounting for approximately 34% of global meat production. One might wonder about the sheer logistical effort required to track such figures, but here we are. This widespread consumption has, quite predictably, led to the development of an immense number of [pork recipes](/List_of_pork_dishes) across every corner of the globe. From the sophisticated, dry-cured [Jamón](/Jam%C3%B3n), crafted from the hind legs of a pig and revered as Spain's most famous culinary export, to [Feijoada](/Feijoada), the hearty national dish of [Brazil](/Brazil) (also a staple in Portugal), traditionally enriched with humble pork trimmings like ears, tail, and feet—the versatility of pork is undeniable.

![Production of pork worldwide, by country in 2021](/File:Pork_production_by_country.svg)
Production of pork worldwide, by country in 2021

According to the [USDA](/USDA)'s [Foreign Agricultural Service](/Foreign_Agricultural_Service), a staggering nearly 100 million metric tons of pork were consumed worldwide in 2006 (based on preliminary data, naturally). This figure is not static, however. The relentless march of urbanization and the steady increase in disposable income have fueled a remarkable surge in pork consumption in [China](/China). In 2006, Chinese consumption alone was a full 20% higher than it had been in 2002, with a further 5% increase optimistically projected for 2007. By 2015, the global appetite had grown even more voracious, with a recorded total of 109.905 million metric tons of pork consumed worldwide. A mere two years later, in 2017, [China](/China) alone accounted for half of all pork consumed globally. It seems when it comes to pork, the world, and particularly [China](/China), has an insatiable hunger.

